<section xml:id="sec-perm" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Permutations</title>

  
<p>
  Arrange the letters <m>A, B, C</m> by taking three at a time.
</p>
<p>
  Here they are:
  <md>
    <mrow> i. \quad \amp = ABC</mrow>
    <mrow> ii. \quad \amp = ACB</mrow>
    <mrow> iii. \quad \amp = BAC</mrow>
    <mrow> iv. \quad \amp = BCA</mrow>
    <mrow> v. \quad \amp = CAB</mrow>
    <mrow> vi. \quad \amp = CBA</mrow>
  </md>
  so again <m>6</m> permutations.
</p>

<p>
 Find all permutations of letters <m>A, B, C, D</m> by taking three at a time.
</p>


<tabular halign="center">
  <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
    <cell>ABC </cell>
    <cell>ABD </cell>
    <cell>ACD </cell>
    <cell>BCD </cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell><m>6 </m> </cell>
    <cell><m>6 </m></cell>
    <cell><m>6</m></cell>
    <cell><m>6</m></cell>
   </row>
 </tabular>
<p>
  Hence, total of <m>6+6+6+6=24.</m> different arrangements.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-perm1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The number of permutations of <m>n</m> different objects taken <m>r</m> at a time, where <m>0\lt r \leq n</m> 
      and the objects do not repeat, is given by <m> (P,r) \quad \text{ or, } \quad  ^nP_r</m>. Here, 
      <me>
      ^nP_r = n(n-1)(n-2) \ldots (n-r+1) = \frac{n!}{(n-r)!}.
      </me>
      </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<theorem xml:id="thm-perm2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The number of permutations of <m>n</m> things of which <m>p</m> are alike of one kind, 
      <m>q</m> are alike of another kind and remaining all are distinct is given by 
      <me>
        \frac{n!}{p!\times q!}.
        </me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>


</section>